<assessment id="u3_m3_binomial4_tutor2">
   <title>Tutor</title>
<page>   
   <question id="q1">
      <body>
         <p>The mean and standard deviation of X are:</p>
      </body>
      <multiple_choice shuffle="false">
         <choice value="Res1">&#956;<sub>X</sub> = 12.55, &#963;<sub>X</sub> = 525</choice>
         <choice value="Res2">&#956;<sub>X</sub> = 525, &#963;<sub>X</sub> = 12.55</choice>
         <choice value="Res3">&#956;<sub>X</sub> = 525, &#963;<sub>X</sub> = 157.5</choice>
      </multiple_choice>
      <part>
         <response match="Res1" score="0">
            <feedback>Incorrect. It seems like you did the right calculations, but
               just got the notation mixed up. &#956;<sub>X</sub> is the mean, and
               &#963;<sub>X</sub> is the standard deviation.</feedback>
         </response>
         <response match="Res2" score="10">
            <feedback>Good
                  <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220552-0500"?>j<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220552-0500" content="J"?>ob!
                  Indeed, since X is a binomial random variable, &#956;<sub>X</sub> = np = 750(.7) =
                  525. &#963;<sup>2</sup><sub>X</sub> = np(1 - p) = 750(.7)(.3) = 157.5, and
                  therefore &#963;<sub>X</sub> = sqrt(157.5) =
                  12.55.<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220631-0500"?> (Note
                  that "sqrt" stands for square root.)<?oxy_insert_end?></feedback>
         </response>
         <response match="Res3" score="0">
            <feedback>Incorrect. Your mean is correct. However, we are asking for
               the standard deviation, &#963;<sub>X</sub>, and 157.5 is the variance. Get &#963;<sub>X</sub> by taking the square root of 157.5, 
               and try again.</feedback>
         </response>
      </part>
   </question>
</page></assessment>
